    {
      "document_id": "doc-wt-002",
      "filename": "retina-visit-note-2025-10-22.txt",
      "document_type": "prior_visit_note",
      "document_date": "2025-10-22",
      "content": {
        "format": "text",
        "text_content": "MONTZKA EYE CLINIC - RETINA SERVICE\nOFFICE VISIT NOTE\n\nPatient: William R. Thompson | DOB: 08/22/1946 (79 years old)\nDate of Service: October 22, 2025\nProvider: Sarah Morrison, MD\nVisit Type: Treat-and-extend follow-up, neovascular AMD OD\n\nINTERVAL HISTORY:\nMr. Thompson returns 10 weeks after his third Eylea injection (August 12, 2025). At his last three visits the macula was dry at 7-week intervals, so we trialed an extension to 10 weeks. Today he reports mild recurrence of distortion in the right eye over the past week. He remains independent at home. His main concern is keeping his reading and driving vision.\n\nEXAMINATION:\nVisual acuity (corrected): OD 20/30 (was 20/25), OS 20/30.\nIOP: OD 15, OS 14 mmHg.\nDilated fundus exam OD: recurrent subfoveal fluid, no new hemorrhage. OS: stable drusen, no conversion.\n\nIMAGING:\nOCT OD today shows recurrent subretinal fluid with central retinal thickness increased to 331 microns (from 264 microns on September 30). The left eye continues to show intermediate dry AMD with soft drusen and no evidence of neovascular conversion.\n\nASSESSMENT:\n1. Neovascular age-related macular degeneration, right eye (H35.3211) - recurrent activity at extended 10-week interval after three consecutive dry visits at 7-week intervals.\n2. Intermediate dry AMD, left eye (H35.3120) - stable; continue AREDS2 and home Amsler monitoring.\n\nPLAN:\nIntravitreal aflibercept (Eylea) 2mg OD administered today without complication (injection #4).\nRecurrent subretinal fluid at the 10-week interval confirms he cannot maintain extension beyond 7 weeks. We will return to 7-week dosing intervals and do not plan to extend again. Follow-up OCT and injection in 4 weeks to confirm the macula has dried, then resume the 7-week cycle.\nReturn precautions reviewed (sudden vision loss, new distortion, curtain or shadow).\n\n[ELECTRONIC SIGNATURE APPLIED]\nSarah Morrison, MD - Vitreoretinal Surgery\nSigned: 10/22/2025 16:40"
      },
      "extracted_data": {
